#X text 39 48 Bangs are control rate triggers. The audio signal counterpart is an impulse \, which is a single sample value different than 0 (usually 1) \, so when an object responds to an impulse it respinds at that exact sample., f 67;
#X text 39 114 It must be clear from the last example that if an audio object only takes bangs or control messages to trigger/set something \, it can only set a single parameter for the whole audio block. For bangs \, which usually trigger an event \, it means you can only trigger something at the beggining of a block. Let's have a look at this example with the [decay~] object from ELSE \, which takes both bangs and impulses. Instead of [metro] from Vanilla \, we use a [tempo] object from ELSE \, which is similar and sends bangs at a BPM value by default. The [tempo~] object is the signal counterpart and sends impulses., f 67;
#X text 39 502 Even though an impulse will effectively have a better timing resolution \, it is definitely imperceptible for humans in the case above \, where triggers happen at every one second. We'll see examples in this tutorial when audio rate triggeting is necessary \, like when syncing oscillators. We'll also measure this difference in the next examples. The thing to take from this example is that \, in many cases \, a control rate event will be just fine \, and it is more efficient \, if you care about efficiency., f 67;
